Perform Friedman Test and Nemenyi Post-Hoc Analysis with Output Saving

friedman.nemenyi.Rd

This function conducts a Friedman test to evaluate significant differences among multiple methods based on provided data. If significant differences are detected, the function proceeds with a Nemenyi post-hoc test to identify which methods differ significantly. The results, including a difference matrix, Critical Difference (CD) plot, and p-values plot, are saved as CSV and PDF files.

friedman.nemenyi(data, save, measure.name, width = 7, height = 5, cex = 1.2)

Arguments

data

A data frame where each row represents a method and each column represents an observation or measurement.

measure.name

A string used as the base name for output files.

width

Numeric value indicating the width of the PDF plots.

height

Numeric value indicating the height of the PDF plots.

cex

Numeric value controlling the size of text in the plots.

save.dir

A string specifying the directory where output files will be saved.

Value

A data frame with the following columns:

ChiSquare

The Chi-Square statistic from the Friedman test.

pValue

The p-value from the Friedman test.

Method

The method used for the Friedman test.

CriticalDifference

The Critical Difference from the Nemenyi test.

Result

Indicates whether the methods are significantly different.

Details

The function saves the following files:

CSV File

A CSV file containing the results data frame.

Difference Matrix

A CSV file containing the difference matrix from the Nemenyi post-hoc test.

CD Plot

A PDF file containing the Critical Difference plot.

p-Values Plot

A PDF file containing the p-values plot.

Examples

# Example usage:
# Assuming 'my_data' is a data frame and 'output_dir' is the directory for saving outputs
result <- friedman.nemenyi(my_data, "output.dir", "my.measure", 7, 5, 1.2)
#> Error in friedman.nemenyi(my_data, "output.dir", "my.measure", 7, 5, 1.2): unused arguments ("my.measure", 7, 5, 1.2)
